catalog.title: Health Behavior Change
catalog.description: Health Behavior Change is an overview of the health behaviors contributing most dramatically to increased morbidity and mortality in the United States. The course emphasizes public health interventions and strategies to promote healthy behaviors and discourage unhealthy behaviors. The course examines consequences, patterns, risk factors, and change/interventions for each behavior or problem. Behaviors are examined from multiples perspectives (e.g., individual, social, environmental) and with a systems perspective in mind, illuminating the interconnecting influences on behaviors. Health behaviors and behavior change interventions are presented in the context of current research and theory. The course also examines the role of health disparities, public health policy, current debate, health behavior theory and emerging research.

notes.note:
Entrepreneurial Solutions for Addressing Food Access Disparities

This course will provide students with practical experience addressing food access disparities using principals of social entrepreneurship. The course will include both formal weekly online classes and experiential service learning working with a team that is developing a new mobile produce market program. Weekly classes will alternate between understanding the causes of food apartheid and solutions that promote health equity and practical steps for starting a mobile produce market or similar food enterprise. In addition, each student will be assigned to work remotely with a team of mobile market practitioners based in the United States. The goal will be to work with the organization to produce a final project to address the organizationÂ¿s needs such as a community engagement plan, a health equity impact analysis, a social marketing campaign or a food education lesson plan. Students will have access to experts who can provide feedback and support to complete assignments

Indigenous populations experience lower life expectancy, lower quality of life, and a higher prevalence of several chronic and infectious diseases in comparison to other populations within their respective regions, counties, states and countries.  Using an evidence-based approach, this course will provide an overview of the many health issues impacting Indigenous populations today  and into the future.  This course is designed to embrace the concepts of the social determinants of health, intergenerational trauma, health equity, and racism and health.   Students will examine the real histories of Indigenous peoples, cultural norms and adaptations, traditional healing and the impacts of colonization at the advancement of westernization.   This course is intended to raise awareness and support future public health leaders who become experts in promoting better health worldwide.

catalog.title: Refugee Health
catalog.description: This course provides an introduction to both the global and local health issues related to refugee populations. Health, cultural issues, barriers to care, and services for refugee populations in the United States will be featured, with an emphasis on Western New York's (WNY) refugee groups. Global historical and policy issues related to refugees and refugee health also will be studied.

catalog.title: Applied Statistics for PH
catalog.description: This graduate level course is designed to provide an introduction to the application of statistics to public health research questions. The course will also cover principles of data management and data verification.   It will not provide instruction regarding statistics (STA 527 is a prerequisite), rather, we will build upon an individualÂ¿s statistical training to provide instruction in the use of common statistical packages to answer statistical questions.  The course will introduce different statistical packages to allow students to develop a proficiency in different packages.    The course will have both in-class meetings as well as remote computer laboratory sessions (students will not be required to be in a classroom setting or online for the laboratory sessions, rather, students will complete these laboratory sessions at a location and time of their choice).

catalog.title: Tobacco Control
catalog.description: Designed to prepare students to confront the practical problems of controlling tobacco use through local, state, and national public health agencies. In addition to providing core knowledge on tobacco-related issues, the course will include skills-based training that may be useful in future employment.

catalog.title: Public Health Teams & Practice
catalog.description: This course will provide students with the foundations needed for public health professionals to work with other health professionals along with key leadership skills. This class will also provide students with communication and conflict resolution skills. Documentation and presentation of the skills students learn is also another area that will be covered during this course.
